Part I - Prosper Loan Data¶

by Fraser Fernandes¶

Introduction¶

The Prosper Loan Dataset consists of 113,937 loan records, each with 81 variables. In our analysis, we aim to examine key metrics and identify the variables that influence them.

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

This dataset has variables which rely heavily on analysis to make decisions. For example what loan amounts should be approved and at what intrest rates. What factors can predit the charge off of a loan in the future. These are some dependent features we can look into for our analysis.

import pandas as pd

def convert_columns_to_int(df, columns):
    for column in columns:
        df[column] = pd.to_numeric(df[column], errors='coerce').astype(pd.Int64Dtype())
    return df

# Correcting format of date columns

date_cols = ['DateCreditPulled', 'ListingCreationDate', 'ClosedDate', 'FirstRecordedCreditLine', 'LoanOriginationDate', ]

def convert_date(data, columns):
    for col in columns:
        data[col] = pd.to_datetime(data[col], errors='coerce')
        data[col] = data[col].dt.date
    return data

data = convert_date(data, date_cols)

Feature engineering:¶
In [7]:
# Calculating the difference between borrower rate and lender yield
data['margin'] = data['BorrowerRate']-data['LenderYield']

# Calculating the difference between Borrower APR and Borrower Rate (Additional Cost)
data['add_cost'] = data['BorrowerAPR']-data['BorrowerRate']

# Calculating approximate credit score
data['CreditScore'] = (data['CreditScoreRangeLower']+data['CreditScoreRangeUpper']+1)/2

# Displaying statuses of closed loans
data['Loan_Status'] = data['LoanStatus'].apply(lambda x: 'Past Due Date' if 'Past Due' in x else x)

# Ensure the necessary columns are clean and formatted correctly
data['LoanStatus'] = data['LoanStatus'].astype('category')
data['CreditGrade'] = data['CreditGrade'].astype('category')

# Converting ListingCategory (numeric) to string format
category_map = {
    0: "Not Available", 1: "Debt Consolidation", 2: "Home Improvement", 3: "Business", 4: "Personal Loan",
    5: "Student Use", 6: "Auto", 7: "Other", 8: "Baby&Adoption", 9: "Boat", 10: "Cosmetic Procedure",
    11: "Engagement Ring", 12: "Green Loans", 13: "Household Expenses", 14: "Large Purchases",
    15: "Medical/Dental", 16: "Motorcycle", 17: "RV", 18: "Taxes", 19: "Vacation", 20: "Wedding Loans"
}

data['ListingCategory (numeric)'] = data['ListingCategory (numeric)'].map(category_map).astype(str)
data.rename(columns={'ListingCategory (numeric)': 'ListingCategory'}, inplace=True)

Univariate Exploration¶

Distribution of Loan Amounts¶

Question: How are the loans distributed in terms of amounts?

We will take a look at the distribution of Loan Amounts using a Histogram.

In [12]:
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
bins = np.arange(df['LoanAmount'].min(), df['LoanAmount'].max() + 1000, 1000)

ax = sns.histplot(df['LoanAmount'], bins=bins, kde=False, color='#17BEBB', alpha=1)
ax.grid(True, axis='y', color='grey', linestyle='-', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.2)
ax.xaxis.grid(False)

def prepare_data_for_stacked_chart(df, category):
    # Create a crosstab and normalize by index
    crosstab = pd.crosstab(df[category], df['LoanStatus'], normalize='index')
    # Specify the desired order of the categories
    desired_order = ['Completed','Chargedoff']
    # Filter the columns based on the desired order and existing columns in crosstab
    columns = [col for col in desired_order if col in crosstab.columns]
    # Reorder the columns according to the desired order
    if columns:
        crosstab = crosstab[columns]
    return crosstab

def plot_stacked_chart(data, title, xlabel):
    colors = ['#4E79A7','#F28E2B' ]
    # Plot the data
    data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6), color=colors)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel('Percentage')
    plt.grid(True, linewidth=1, alpha=0.2)
    plt.gca().xaxis.grid(False)
    plt.legend(title='Loan Status')
    
    plt.show()

for var in all_categorical:
    if var in df1.columns:
        data = prepare_data_for_stacked_chart(df1, var)
        plot_stacked_chart(data, f'Loan Status Distribution by {var}', var)
    else:
        print(f"{var} is not in the DataFrame columns.")

In the above 100% Bar Charts, we explore some interesting relationships between the final status of loans and various categorical variables.

Ordinal Categories:

  • CreditGrade & ProsperRating (Alpha) demonstrate a consistent increase in the proportion of charged-off loans as the grades/ratings decrease.
  • There is an observable rise in charged-off loans as ProsperScore and ProsperRating (Numeric) increase.
  • As CreditScores rise, we consistently see a decrease in the proportion of charged-off loans.
  • Term duration also significantly correlates with the proportion of charged-off loans; longer terms are associated with a higher likelihood of loans being charged off. It is possible that there is something else impacting the loan charge-offs. For example, if larger loan amounts are likely to have longer terms, it's possible that the loans are being charged off because the amount is large rather than the term.

Nominal Categories:

  • The proportion of charged-off loans varies considerably across Occupations. Some occupations exhibit more than 25% of their loans charged off, while others have no charged-off loans at all.
  • The variation in charged-off loans by BorrowerState is notable. Wyoming features the lowest proportion of charged-off loans, followed by Delaware, whereas Alaska and Michigan display the highest proportions. This discrepancy suggests that additional factors might influence these outcomes.
  • EmploymentStatus, Occupation, and ListingCategory (purpose of the loan) yield significant data on the disparities in loan outcomes, with variations markedly evident in terms of charged-off versus completed loans.
  • TradesOpenedLast6Months displays a steady increase in the proportion of charged-off loans, though this pattern becomes inconsistent with higher values. The limited number of data entries at these levels likely causes each entry to disproportionately affect the proportions. A similar pattern is observed in PublicRecordsLast10Years, where the proportion of charged-off loans increases with the number of years.

These highlighted relationships offer a glimpse into the dynamics influencing loan outcomes and suggest areas for deeper analysis.

Observation¶

As the CreditGrade decreases, we observe a contraction in the interquartile range (IQR), with both Q1 and the maximum values decreasing, along with the median value. This suggests a concentration of data points in the lower loan amounts for lower grades. Notably, some Credit Grades show larger loan amounts than expected, especially in lower credit grades like HR.

# Define a custom function to use Matplotlib's hist2d
def hist2d_plot(x, y, **kwargs):
    cbar_label = kwargs.pop("cbar_label", "Density")
    h = plt.hist2d(x, y, bins=30, cmap="magma_r", cmin=1)
    if "cbar" not in plt.gcf().texts:
        cbar = plt.colorbar(h[3], ax=plt.gca())
        cbar.set_label(cbar_label)

# Creating a fasceted grid
g = sns.FacetGrid(data=df1, col="CreditGrade", col_wrap=4, height=4)

# Pass the custom plot function to FacetGrid
g.map(hist2d_plot, "LoanAmount", "BorrowerRate", cbar_label="Density")

# Set axis labels
g.set_axis_labels("Loan Amount ($)", "Borrower Rate (%)")
g.set_titles("{col_name}")

plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • Loan Amount and Credit Score: There is a generally positive relationship between these two variables, indicating that borrowers with higher loan amounts tend to have better credit scores.
  • Borrower Rate: Appears to be negatively correlated with both Loan Amount and Credit Score overall. This suggests that borrowers with higher loan amounts or better credit scores are likely to secure lower interest rates.

2. Segmented by Credit Grade¶

  • When data is segmented by Credit Grade, the relationships between these variables show distinct patterns:
    • Higher Grades (AA, A, B): Exhibit a positive relationship between Loan Amount and Borrower Rate, potentially reflecting specific borrowing dynamics for individuals with higher credit grades.
    • Lower Grades (C, D, E, HR): Concentrated in the low loan amount, high borrower rate regions, creating an overall negative correlation across all grades combined.
  • This highlights how lower credit grades skew the aggregate data due to their disproportionate influence.

3. Loan Status Analysis¶

  • By including Loan Status ("Completed" and "Chargedoff") in the analysis, we gain additional insights:
    • Higher Credit Grades (AA, A, B): Show a lower proportion of Chargedoff loans, indicating lower credit risk.
    • Lower Credit Grades (C, D, E, HR): Show a higher proportion of Chargedoff loans, reflecting greater credit risk.

4. Implications¶

  • These observations suggest that credit grades strongly influence borrowing dynamics, loan approval trends, and default risks.
  • For lower credit grades, borrowers are more likely to experience higher interest rates and a greater risk of loan default.

Conclusions¶

The analysis reveals that creditworthiness plays an important role in determining loan amounts, interest rates, and repayment outcomes. Borrowers with better credit profiles enjoy larger loans, lower rates, and higher completion rates, while lower grades experience higher rates, smaller loans, and increased default risks. These insights underscore the importance of risk assessment and loan structuring in managing loan portfolios effectively. Here is a deeper summary of our findings:

Summary Findings¶

Loan Amount Distribution¶

  • Loan amounts are positively skewed, with higher frequencies at round figures, indicating borrower preferences for round-number loans.
  • Larger loans tend to be associated with better credit scores and lower borrower rates.

Loan Status Trends¶

  • Nearly 50% of loans are active, while 33.4% have been successfully completed.
  • Charged-off loans account for 10.5%, with clear correlations to lower credit grades, longer loan terms, and higher borrower rates.
  • Employment status, borrower state, and occupation influence loan outcomes significantly.

Borrower Rate Analysis¶

  • Borrower rates exhibit positive skewness, with a peak frequency between 15%-16% and an unusual spike at 32%.
  • Borrowers with better credit scores or larger loans secure lower interest rates.
  • Borrower rates strongly correlate with estimated losses (0.95) and returns (0.79), emphasizing higher rates for riskier loans.

Credit Grade Insights¶

  • Higher credit grades (e.g., AA, A, B) are associated with lower interest rates, larger loans, and fewer defaults.
  • Lower credit grades (e.g., C, D, E, HR) face higher interest rates, smaller loan amounts, and a greater likelihood of default.

Key Bivariate and Multivariate Relationships¶

  • A positive relationship exists between Loan Amount and Credit Score, while Borrower Rate shows a negative correlation with both.
  • Longer loan terms are associated with an increased likelihood of defaults.
  • Segmented data highlights distinct patterns: higher grades benefit from favorable borrowing dynamics, while lower grades experience financial constraints.
